    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, what do you mean by \"goblin's ears\"? That sounded really weird. Can you just stick to the technical explanation? I'm confused about the blockage part—specifically, if the pitot tube is blocked by something like an insect or ice, how exactly does that change the pressure reading on the gauge?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the technical explanation.\n\nWhen the pitot tube is partially blocked, the pressure differential is disrupted. The pitot tube measures the pressure of the free stream air, and if it's blocked, the pressure reading becomes skewed. Think of it like a narrow, winding tunnel – if the tunnel is blocked by an object, the air flowing through it will change its path, creating a different pressure reading.\n\nIn the case of a pitot tube blocked by an insect or ice, the air flowing through the tube will be restricted, causing the air to accelerate and create a higher pressure reading on the gauge. This is because the air is forced to flow through a smaller area, increasing its velocity and pressure. Conversely, if the blockage is on the other side of the tube, the pressure reading will be lower.\n\nThe airspeed indicator will display an incorrect airspeed reading, which can lead to incorrect altitude and airspeed decisions. To avoid this, pilots need to monitor the pitot-static system and take corrective action if the tube is blocked or damaged.",
      "source": "target",
